    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-11-07T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-11-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/5296: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-11-07T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 7, 1931—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>36. Your 52, November 7, 4 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d167fn11">Not printed.</note>
                    In view of receipt by you of Mr. Venizelos’ letter<note n="12" xml:id="d167fn12">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_216">p. 216</ref>.</note>
                    stating that the Greek Government accepts without reservations of any sort the
                    President’s proposal, Mr. Venizelos may now with this Government’s approval
                    inform the International Financial Commission that the Greek payment due
                    November 10 may be held by the Commission pending further instructions upon the
                    understanding that the funds in question are being held by the Commission for
                    the account of this Government pending favorable action by Congress on the
                    President’s proposal which action is expected soon after Congress reconvenes, in
                    December. You may inform the Commission in the same sense.</p>
                <pb facs="0329" n="215" xml:id="pg_215"/>
                <p>It is of course understood that immediately following such favorable action by
                    Congress the payment made by Greece on July 1, last, and the funds mentioned
                    above will be returned or released and that Greece will be relieved of other
                    payments due during the debt suspension year.</p>
                <p>Please keep Department promptly informed of developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
